window.TEST_DATA = {"1": {"questext": "The Treaty of Allahabad, which laid the foundation for British political control in Bengal, was signed in which year by Robert Clive?","options": ["1757","1760","1765","1767"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1765</b><br><br>Robert Clive, who served as Governor of Bengal in two spells (1757–1760 and 1765–1767), signed the <b>Treaty of Allahabad</b> in <b>1765</b>. During his second tenure, he introduced the <b>Dual Administration (Diarchy)</b> system in Bengal, under which revenue collection and administration were separated. His tenure also witnessed the <b>White Mutiny</b>, an uprising of European officers protesting reduced allowances.","expimage": ""},
"2": {"questext": "Robert Clive, regarded as the Father of Dyarchy in Bengal, is credited with founding which of the following?","options": ["Asiatic Society of Bengal","Society for Trade","Calcutta Madarasa","Fort William College"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Society for Trade</b><br><br>Robert Clive established the <b>'Society for Trade'</b> during his second governorship. He is also remembered for his victory in the <b>Battle of Plassey (1757)</b>, which laid the foundation of British political power in India. Clive is regarded as the <b>Father of Dyarchy in Bengal</b> due to the dual system of administration he introduced.","expimage": ""},
"3": {"questext": "Robert Clive was given the title of 'Umara' by which two rulers?","options": ["Salawat Jung and Alamgir-II","Shah Alam-II and Shuja-ud-Daula","Mir Jafar and Mir Qasim","Siraj-ud-Daulah and Salawat Jung"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Salawat Jung and Alamgir-II</b><br><br>Robert Clive was given the title of <b>'Umara'</b> by <b>Salawat Jung</b> and Mughal Emperor <b>Alamgir-II</b>. Clive also established three army centres to strengthen British military presence — at <b>Allahabad, Munger, and Bankipur</b> (West Bengal).","expimage": ""},
"4": {"questext": "John Zephaniah Holwell, who served as temporary Governor of Bengal after Robert Clive in 1760, is best known for narrating which incident?","options": ["The Battle of Plassey","The Black Hole incident","The Battle of Buxar","The White Mutiny"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>The Black Hole incident</b><br><br><b>John Zephaniah Holwell</b> was made the temporary Governor of Bengal in <b>1760</b> after Robert Clive's departure. He is best remembered for narrating the incident of the <b>'Black Hole of Calcutta'</b>, describing the suffocation deaths of British prisoners held by Siraj-ud-Daulah's forces in 1756.","expimage": ""},
"5": {"questext": "Henry Vansittart, Governor of Bengal from 1760 to 1765, held office during which major battle?","options": ["Battle of Plassey (1757)","Battle of Buxar (1764)","Battle of Wandiwash (1760)","Battle of Ferozeshah (1845)"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Battle of Buxar (1764)</b><br><br><b>Henry Vansittart</b> served as Governor of Bengal from <b>1760 to 1765</b>. His tenure is notable for the <b>Battle of Buxar</b> fought in <b>1764</b>, in which the combined forces of Mir Qasim, the Nawab of Awadh, and the Mughal Emperor were defeated by the British East India Company.","expimage": ""},
"6": {"questext": "Harry Verelst, who served as Governor of Bengal from 1767 to 1769, held office during which administrative system?","options": ["Permanent Settlement","Ryotwari System","Dual Administration (Diarchy)","Mahalwari System"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Dual Administration (Diarchy)</b><br><br><b>Harry Verelst</b> served as Governor of Bengal from <b>1767 to 1769</b>, a period during which the <b>Dual Administration (Diarchy)</b> system introduced by Robert Clive continued to operate in Bengal, separating revenue collection from actual administration.","expimage": ""},
"7": {"questext": "John Cartier, Governor of Bengal from 1769 to 1772, held office during which major disaster?","options": ["Bengal Famine of 1770","Great Famine of 1896-97","Santhal Uprising of 1855-56","Orissa Famine of 1866"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Bengal Famine of 1770</b><br><br><b>John Cartier</b> served as Governor of Bengal from <b>1769 to 1772</b>. His tenure is remembered chiefly for the devastating <b>Bengal Famine of 1770</b>, which killed millions of people and exposed the exploitative revenue policies of the East India Company.","expimage": ""},
"8": {"questext": "Warren Hastings, who served as Governor of Bengal from 1772 to 1774, holds which distinction in British Indian administrative history?","options": ["First Viceroy of India","First Governor-General of Bengal and last Governor of Bengal","First Governor-General of India","Founder of the Asiatic Society"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>First Governor-General of Bengal and last Governor of Bengal</b><br><br><b>Warren Hastings</b> served as <b>Governor of Bengal from 1772 to 1774</b>. He holds the distinction of being the <b>last Governor of Bengal</b> before the post was upgraded, making him also the <b>first Governor-General of Bengal</b> when the office was created in 1774.","expimage": ""},
"9": {"questext": "As Governor-General of Bengal (1774-1785), Warren Hastings shifted the treasury from Murshidabad to Calcutta and ended which system?","options": ["Permanent Settlement","Dual Administration (Diarchy)","Subsidiary Alliance","Doctrine of Lapse"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Dual Administration (Diarchy)</b><br><br>As <b>Governor-General of Bengal (1774-1785)</b>, Warren Hastings brought an <b>end to the Diarchy</b> in Bengal and shifted the <b>treasury from Murshidabad to Calcutta</b>. During his tenure, <b>Zamindars were given judicial powers</b>, and <b>civil and criminal courts</b> were established in each district to streamline administration.","expimage": ""},
"10": {"questext": "The Supreme Court at Calcutta, established by Warren Hastings, was set up in which year?","options": ["1774","1781","1784","1793"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1774</b><br><br>Warren Hastings established the <b>Supreme Court at Calcutta</b> in <b>1774</b>. In <b>1781</b>, he founded the <b>Calcutta Madarasa</b>, the first madarasa, for the promotion of Islamic studies. In <b>1784</b>, the <b>Asiatic Society of Bengal</b> was established under his patronage by <b>William Jones</b>.","expimage": ""},
"11": {"questext": "Warren Hastings resigned as Governor-General in 1785 in protest against which legislation?","options": ["Regulating Act of 1773","Pitt's India Bill","Charter Act of 1793","Government of India Act 1858"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Pitt's India Bill</b><br><br>Warren Hastings resigned in <b>1785</b> in protest against <b>Pitt's India Bill</b>. Upon returning to England, he was <b>impeached</b> for his conduct in India by <b>Edmund Burke</b>. A case was filed against him, but he was ultimately <b>acquitted of all charges in 1795</b>.","expimage": ""},
"12": {"questext": "The English translation of the 'Gita' and 'Hitopadesha' during Warren Hastings' tenure was carried out by whom?","options": ["William Jones","Charles Wilkins","Jonathan Duncan","Max Mueller"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Charles Wilkins</b><br><br>During Warren Hastings' tenure, <b>Charles Wilkins</b> translated the <b>'Gita' and 'Hitopadesha'</b> into English. This period also saw the <b>First Maratha War (1775-82)</b>, concluded by the <b>Treaty of Salbai (1782)</b>, and the <b>Second Anglo-Mysore War (1780-84)</b>, concluded by the <b>Treaty of Mangalore</b>.","expimage": ""},
"13": {"questext": "The Sanskrit College at Banaras was founded in 1791 during Lord Cornwallis' tenure by whom?","options": ["William Jones","Jonathan Duncan","Charles Wilkins","David Hare"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Jonathan Duncan</b><br><br><b>Jonathan Duncan</b> founded the <b>Sanskrit College at Banaras in 1791</b> during Lord Cornwallis' tenure (1786-1793). The same period saw the introduction of a <b>new Police System (1791)</b> and the <b>Third Anglo-Mysore War (1790-92)</b>, which ended in the defeat of <b>Tipu Sultan</b>.","expimage": ""},
"14": {"questext": "The Cornwallis Code, introduced by Lord Cornwallis, was based on which principle?","options": ["Doctrine of Lapse","Separation of powers","Divide and rule","Subsidiary Alliance"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Separation of powers</b><br><br>Lord Cornwallis introduced the <b>Cornwallis Code</b>, based on the principle of <b>separation of powers</b>, following the <b>Treaty of Seringapatam (1792)</b> that concluded the Third Anglo-Mysore War. In <b>1793</b>, financial and revenue functions were separated from judicial and administrative functions.", "expimage": ""},
"15": {"questext": "Lord Cornwallis, who introduced the Permanent Settlement in Bengal in 1793, is popularly known by which title?","options": ["Father of Local Self-Government","Father of the Civil Services","Father of Modern Education","Father of Indian Agriculture"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Father of the Civil Services</b><br><br>Lord Cornwallis is known as the <b>'Father of the Civil Services'</b>. In <b>1793</b>, he created the post of <b>District Judge</b> and introduced the <b>Permanent Settlement</b> in Bengal, a landmark land revenue system that fixed the revenue payable by zamindars.","expimage": ""},
"16": {"questext": "During Lord Cornwallis' reforms of 1790-92, how many circuit courts were established after Indian judges were abolished?","options": ["Two","Three","Four","Five"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Four</b><br><br>During <b>1790-92</b>, Indian judges were abolished and <b>four circuit courts</b> were established at <b>Calcutta, Dhaka, Murshidabad, and Patna</b>. Lord Cornwallis is also notable as the <b>only Governor-General whose mausoleum</b> is located in <b>Ghazipur</b>, India.","expimage": ""},
"17": {"questext": "Sir John Shore, Governor-General from 1793 to 1798, is best known for his policy of non-interference with which entities?","options": ["European traders","Princely States","Missionaries","Zamindars"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Princely States</b><br><br><b>Sir John Shore</b> (1793-1798) is famous for his <b>Policy of Non-interference with Princely States</b>. During his tenure, the <b>First Charter Act</b> was introduced in <b>1793</b>, and he continued the planning of the <b>Permanent Settlement</b> alongside Lord Cornwallis.","expimage": ""},
"18": {"questext": "Lord Wellesley introduced the Subsidiary Alliance system in 1798 to achieve British Paramountcy. Which state entered this alliance in 1798 itself?","options": ["Mysore","Awadh","Hyderabad","Tanjore"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Hyderabad</b><br><br>Lord Richard Wellesley (1798-1805) introduced the <b>Subsidiary Alliance</b> system in <b>1798</b> to secure British paramountcy. <b>Hyderabad</b> entered the alliance in <b>1798</b>, followed by <b>Mysore and Tanjore (1799)</b>, <b>Awadh (1801)</b>, <b>Peshwa (1802)</b>, <b>Bhonsle (1803)</b>, <b>Scindia (1804)</b>, and <b>Jodhpur & Jaipur (1818)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"19": {"questext": "The Fourth Anglo-Mysore War of 1799, fought during Lord Wellesley's tenure, resulted in the death of which ruler?","options": ["Hyder Ali","Tipu Sultan","Nizam of Hyderabad","Peshwa Baji Rao II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Tipu Sultan</b><br><br>The <b>Fourth Anglo-Mysore War (1799)</b> during Lord Wellesley's tenure resulted in the defeat and death of <b>Tipu Sultan</b>. The <b>Second Anglo-Maratha War (1803-1805)</b> also occurred under Wellesley, leading to the defeat of <b>Scindia, Holkar, and Bhonsle</b>. States such as <b>Mecheri, Bundi, Bharatpur, and Berar</b> also accepted the Subsidiary Alliance system.","expimage": ""},
"20": {"questext": "Lord Wellesley, who called himself the 'Sher of Bengal', formed the Madras Presidency in 1801 after conquering which territories?","options": ["Mysore and Coorg","Tanjore and Carnatic","Sindh and Punjab","Awadh and Bihar"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Tanjore and Carnatic</b><br><br>Lord Wellesley, who called himself the <b>'Sher of Bengal'</b>, formed the <b>Madras Presidency in 1801</b> after conquering <b>Tanjore and Carnatic</b>. In <b>1799</b>, censorship was imposed on the press, considered the <b>first instance of banning the Indian press</b>.","expimage": ""},
"21": {"questext": "During Lord Wellesley's tenure, the British under Lord Lake captured the Red Fort in 1803. Who became the first British Resident there?","options": ["David Ochterlony","Thomas Munro","James Thomson","Charles Metcalfe"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>David Ochterlony</b><br><br>The British, led by <b>Lord Lake</b>, captured the <b>Red Fort in 1803</b>, after which <b>Ochterlony</b> became the <b>first British Resident</b>. Wellesley had also established the <b>Fort William College</b> in Calcutta in <b>1800</b> for training civil servants, but it was closed in <b>1802</b>, with training shifted to Haileybury.","expimage": ""},
"22": {"questext": "The Sepoy Mutiny of Vellore, which occurred during Sir George Barlow's tenure, took place in which year?","options": ["1805","1806","1807","1809"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1806</b><br><br>The <b>Sepoy Mutiny of Vellore</b> occurred in <b>1806</b> during the tenure of <b>Sir George Barlow (1805-1807)</b>. His tenure also saw the <b>end of the Second Anglo-Maratha War in 1805</b>.","expimage": ""},
"23": {"questext": "The Treaty of Amritsar (1809), signed with Maharaja Ranjit Singh, was concluded during the tenure of which Governor-General?",
"options": ["Lord Cornwallis","Minto I","Lord Hastings","Lord Auckland"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Minto I</b><br><br><b>Minto I (1807-1813)</b> signed the <b>Treaty of Amritsar in 1809</b> with <b>Maharaja Ranjit Singh</b>. His tenure also witnessed the passage of the <b>Charter Act of 1813</b>, which ended the East India Company's trade monopoly except in tea and trade with China.","expimage": ""},
"24": {"questext": "The Treaty of Sugauli (1816), signed after the Anglo-Nepal War, was concluded during the tenure of which Governor-General?","options": ["Lord Francis Rawdon Hastings","Minto I","Lord William Bentinck","Lord Amherst"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Francis Rawdon Hastings</b><br><br><b>Lord Francis Rawdon Hastings (1813-1823)</b> concluded the <b>Anglo-Nepal War (1814-1816)</b> with the <b>Treaty of Sugauli (1816)</b>. He also signed the <b>Treaty of Poona (1817)</b> with the Peshwa, setting the stage for further conflict with the Marathas.","expimage": ""},
"25": {"questext": "The Ryotwari Settlement was introduced in Madras in 1820 by which official during Lord Hastings' tenure?","options": ["James Thomson","Thomas Munro","Jonathan Duncan","William Sleeman"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Thomas Munro</b><br><br><b>Thomas Munro</b> introduced the <b>Ryotwari Settlement in Madras in 1820</b> during the tenure of Lord Francis Rawdon Hastings. This period also saw the <b>Third Anglo-Maratha War (1817-1818)</b> and the creation of the <b>Bombay Presidency in 1818</b>.","expimage": ""},
"26": {"questext": "The Mahalwari system of land revenue, implemented in the North-West Province, was introduced by whom?","options": ["Thomas Munro","James Thomson","Jonathan Duncan","Lord Cornwallis"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>James Thomson</b><br><br><b>James Thomson</b> implemented the <b>Mahalwari system</b> of land revenue in the <b>North-West Province</b>. Lord Hastings was given the title <b>'Marquess of Hastings'</b> after the Treaty of Sugauli. During his tenure, <b>David Hare founded Hindu College</b> in Calcutta (1817), and the <b>Tenancy Act of 1822</b> was implemented in Bengal.","expimage": ""},
"27": {"questext": "Lord William Amherst, Governor-General from 1823 to 1828, adopted the Policy of 'Intervention and War', leading to which conflict?","options": ["First Anglo-Mysore War","First Burmese War (1824-1826)","First Afghan War","First Anglo-Sikh War"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>First Burmese War (1824-1826)</b><br><br>Lord William Amherst (1823-1828) adopted the <b>Policy of 'Intervention and War'</b>, which led to the <b>First Burmese War (1824-1826)</b>. The war concluded with the <b>Treaty of Yandabu in 1826</b>.","expimage": ""},
"28": {"questext": "Lord William Bentinck, known as the Father of Modern Western Education in India, abolished Sati in which year?","options": ["1828","1829","1833","1835"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1829</b><br><br>Lord William Bentinck (1828-1835), known as the <b>Father of Modern Western Education in India</b>, abolished the practice of <b>Sati in 1829</b>. In the same year, he also <b>banned female infanticide</b> across British India.","expimage": ""},
"29": {"questext": "The suppression of Thuggee, carried out through military operations from 1830, was led by whom under Lord Bentinck?","options": ["William Sleeman","Andrew Fraser","Thomas Munro","David Ochterlony"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>William Sleeman</b><br><br>The suppression of <b>Thuggee (1829-35)</b> was carried out through military operations led by <b>William Sleeman</b> starting in <b>1830</b>. Bentinck also annexed <b>Mysore (1831), Coorg (1834), and Central Cachar (1834)</b> on charges of misgovernment, alongside the passage of the <b>Charter Act of 1833</b>.","expimage": ""},
"30": {"questext": "By the Charter Act of 1833, the Governor-General of Bengal was elevated to which position?","options": ["Viceroy of India","Governor-General of India","President of the Board of Control","Secretary of State for India"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Governor-General of India</b><br><br>By the <b>Charter Act of 1833</b>, the <b>Governor-General of Bengal was made the Governor-General of India</b>. Lord Bentinck also laid the foundation of the <b>Calcutta Medical College</b> and formed the <b>Law Commission</b> during this period.","expimage": ""},
"31": {"questext": "Macaulay's Minutes on Education, which made English the official language of India, was presented in which year?","options": ["1829","1833","1834","1835"],"correct": "4","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1835</b><br><br><b>Macaulay's Minutes on Education</b> was presented in <b>1835</b>, the same year <b>English was made the official language of India</b>. Lord Bentinck had earlier created the <b>province of Agra in 1834</b>.","expimage": ""},
"32": {"questext": "Charles Metcalfe (1835-1836) is remembered as the 'Liberator of the Press' for passing which law?","options": ["Vernacular Press Act","Press Law of 1835","Official Secrets Act","Arms Act"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Press Law of 1835</b><br><br><b>Charles Metcalfe (1835-1836)</b> passed the famous <b>Press Law</b>, freeing the Indian press from restrictions, earning him the title <b>'Liberator of the Press'</b>. He also concluded a <b>Treaty of Perpetual Friendship</b> with Maharaja Ranjit Singh.","expimage": ""},
"33": {"questext": "The Tripartite Treaty of 1838, signed before the First Afghan War, was concluded between Lord Auckland, Ranjit Singh, and which Afghan ruler?","options": ["Dost Mohammad Khan","Shah Shuja","Akbar Khan","Amir Sher Ali Khan"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Shah Shuja</b><br><br>Lord Auckland (1836-1842) signed the <b>Tripartite Treaty of 1838</b> with <b>Ranjit Singh</b> and the Afghan ruler <b>Shah Shuja</b>, leading to the <b>First Afghan War (1839-42)</b>. During this period, the <b>Sher Shah Suri Marg was renamed the Grand Trunk (GT) Road</b>.","expimage": ""},
"34": {"questext": "Lord Ellenborough (1842-1844), nicknamed the 'Old Man in a Hurry', annexed Sindh in which year?","options": ["1842","1843","1844","1845"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1843</b><br><br>Lord Ellenborough (1842-1844) presided over the <b>termination of the First Afghan War in 1842</b> and the <b>annexation of Sindh in 1843</b>. In <b>1844</b>, <b>slavery was abolished in India</b> during his tenure. He was nicknamed the <b>'Old Man in a Hurry'</b>.","expimage": ""},
"35": {"questext": "The Treaty of Lahore (1846), signed after the First Sikh War, was concluded during the tenure of which Governor-General?","options": ["Lord Ellenborough","Lord Henry Hardinge","Lord Dalhousie","Lord Auckland"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Henry Hardinge</b><br><br>Lord Henry Hardinge (1844-1848) concluded the <b>First Sikh War (1845-1846)</b> with the <b>Treaty of Lahore (1846)</b>. He also prohibited <b>female infanticide and human sacrifice</b> among the <b>Gonds of central India</b>.","expimage": ""},
"36": {"questext": "Lord Dalhousie annexed Punjab in 1849 after which war?","options": ["First Anglo-Sikh War","Second Anglo-Sikh War","Second Burmese War","Third Anglo-Maratha War"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Second Anglo-Sikh War</b><br><br>Lord Dalhousie (1848-1856) <b>annexed Punjab in 1849</b> following the <b>Second Anglo-Sikh War</b>. He also applied the <b>Doctrine of Lapse</b>, capturing <b>Satara (1848)</b>, <b>Jaitpur and Sambalpur (1849)</b>, <b>Baghat (1850)</b>, <b>Udaipur (1852)</b>, <b>Jhansi (1853)</b>, and <b>Nagpur (1854)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"37": {"questext": "The first railway line in India, introduced during Lord Dalhousie's tenure in 1853, connected which two places?","options": ["Calcutta-Agra","Bombay-Thane","Madras-Bangalore","Delhi-Lahore"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Bombay-Thane</b><br><br>Lord Dalhousie introduced <b>Railways between Bombay and Thane in 1853</b>. His tenure also saw the <b>Second Burmese War (1852)</b> and the passage of the <b>Charter Act of 1853</b>.","expimage": ""},
"38": {"questext": "The recruitment of the Civil Service through competitive examinations was introduced during Lord Dalhousie's tenure in which year?","options": ["1851","1853","1854","1856"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1853</b><br><br>Recruitment to the <b>Civil Service through competitive examinations</b> was introduced in <b>1853</b>. The same year saw the introduction of the <b>Telegraph between Calcutta and Agra</b> and the establishment of the <b>Postal System</b>.","expimage": ""},
"39": {"questext": "Wood's Dispatch of 1854, known as the 'Magna Carta of Indian Education', was issued during whose tenure?","options": ["Lord Bentinck","Lord Dalhousie","Lord Canning","Lord Curzon"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Dalhousie</b><br><br><b>Wood's Dispatch (1854)</b>, called the <b>'Magna Carta of Indian Education'</b>, was issued during Lord Dalhousie's tenure. His period also saw the <b>Widow Remarriage Act (1856)</b> and the <b>Santhal Uprising (1855-56)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"40": {"questext": "The annexation of Oudh in 1856 by Lord Dalhousie was based on the report submitted by whom?","options": ["Outram Report","Hunter Commission","Lyall Commission","Welby Commission"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Outram Report</b><br><br>Lord Dalhousie annexed <b>Oudh in 1856</b> based on the <b>Outram Report</b>. He also founded the <b>Public Works Department (PWD)</b> and raised the <b>Gorkha Regiment</b> during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"41": {"questext": "Which hill station was made the summer capital of British India during Lord Dalhousie's tenure?","options": ["Darjeeling","Shimla","Nainital","Mussoorie"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Shimla</b><br><br><b>Shimla</b> was made the <b>summer capital of British India</b> under Lord Dalhousie. His tenure also saw the passage of the <b>Post Office Act (1854)</b> and the merger of <b>Sikkim into India</b>.","expimage": ""},
"42": {"questext": "The 'Non-Regulation System', which brought newly acquired territories under direct rule via a Deputy Governor for Bengal, was created by whom?","options": ["Lord Cornwallis","Lord Bentinck","Lord Dalhousie","Lord Canning"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Dalhousie</b><br><br>Lord Dalhousie created the post of <b>Deputy Governor for Bengal</b>, bringing newly acquired territories under direct rule through the <b>'Non-Regulation System'</b>. His <b>Wood's Dispatch (1854)</b> abandoned Macaulay's 'drip system' (downward filtration theory) in education. He is also credited with <b>separating the military department</b> from the public department, creating it as a new department.","expimage": ""},
"43": {"questext": "The three universities of Calcutta, Bombay, and Madras were established in 1857 during whose tenure?","options": ["Lord Dalhousie","Lord Canning","Lord Elgin I","Sir John Lawrence"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Canning</b><br><br>Lord Canning (1856-1862) oversaw the establishment of the <b>three universities of Calcutta, Bombay, and Madras in 1857</b>. His tenure also witnessed <b>Queen Victoria's Proclamation and the Government of India Act, 1858</b>, along with the <b>Indian Councils Act of 1861</b>.","expimage": ""},
"44": {"questext": "Lord Canning, the last Governor-General of India, was in office during which major uprising?","options": ["Santhal Uprising","Revolt of 1857","Vellore Mutiny","Indigo Revolt"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Revolt of 1857</b><br><br>Lord Canning was the <b>last Governor-General of India</b> and presided over the <b>Revolt of 1857</b>. During his tenure, the <b>Indian Penal Code (IPC)</b> was enacted in <b>1860</b>.","expimage": ""},
"45": {"questext": "Lord Canning became the first Viceroy of India following the enactment of which act?","options": ["Charter Act of 1853","Government of India Act, 1858","Indian Councils Act, 1861","Pitt's India Act"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Government of India Act, 1858</b><br><br>Lord Canning became the <b>first Viceroy of India</b> following the <b>Government of India Act, 1858</b>, which ended the East India Company's rule and transferred direct control to the <b>British Crown</b>. The <b>Widow Remarriage Act (1856)</b> was also implemented during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"46": {"questext": "Income tax was imposed for the first time in India in 1860 during Lord Canning's tenure. Who introduced it?","options": ["James Wilson","Andrew Fraser","Thomas Raleigh","James Thomson"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>James Wilson</b><br><br>Income tax was imposed for the <b>first time in India</b> in <b>1860</b>, introduced by the British economist <b>James Wilson</b>. The <b>Indigo Revolt</b> had also broken out in <b>September 1859</b> during Canning's tenure.","expimage": ""},
"47": {"questext": "Lord Elgin I, who served as Viceroy from 1862 to 1863, is best known for suppressing which movement?","options": ["Wahabi Movement","Kuka Movement","Home Rule Movement","Faraizi Movement"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Wahabi Movement</b><br><br>Lord Elgin I (1862-1863) is remembered chiefly for <b>suppressing the Wahabi Movement</b>, a militant Islamic reformist movement that opposed British rule in India.","expimage": ""},
"48": {"questext": "The High Courts of Bombay, Calcutta, and Madras were established in 1865 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Elgin I","Sir John Lawrence","Lord Mayo","Lord Northbrook"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Sir John Lawrence</b><br><br>Sir John Lawrence (1864-1869) oversaw the establishment of <b>High Courts in Bombay, Calcutta, and Madras in 1865</b>. His tenure also witnessed the <b>Bhutan War (1865)</b> and steps taken towards <b>economic decentralisation</b>.","expimage": ""},
"49": {"questext": "Lord Mayo, who founded Mayo College in Ajmer for the education of Indian princes, was assassinated in 1872 at which location?","options": ["Calcutta","Port Blair, Andaman","Delhi","Bombay"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Port Blair, Andaman</b><br><br>Lord Mayo (1869-1872) was <b>assassinated in the Andaman Islands (Port Blair) in 1872</b>. He founded <b>Mayo College in Ajmer</b> for the education of Indian princes.","expimage": ""},
"50": {"questext": "Lord Mayo, considered the father of the Indian Agriculture Department, oversaw the first census of India in which year?","options": ["1861","1867","1872","1881"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1872</b><br><br>Lord Mayo is considered the <b>father of the Indian Agriculture Department</b> for establishing it. The <b>first census of India</b> was also conducted in <b>1872</b> during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"51": {"questext": "The Brahmo Marriage Act was passed during the tenure of which Viceroy, who also witnessed the Prince of Wales' visit to India (1875-76)?","options": ["Lord Mayo","Lord Northbrook","Lord Lytton","Lord Ripon"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Northbrook</b><br><br>Lord Northbrook (1872-1876) presided over the passage of the <b>Brahmo Marriage Act</b> and the <b>Prince of Wales' visit to India (1875-76)</b>. The <b>Kuka Revolt (1872)</b> also occurred during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"52": {"questext": "Queen Victoria assumed the title of 'Empress of India' (Kaiser-e-Hind) during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Northbrook","Lord Lytton","Lord Ripon","Lord Dufferin"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Lytton</b><br><br>Queen Victoria assumed the title of <b>'Empress of India' (Kaiser-e-Hind)</b> during Lord Lytton's tenure (1876-1880). The <b>Mohammedan Anglo-Oriental College</b> at Aligarh was also encouraged by <b>Syed Ahmed Khan</b> during this period. The <b>Vernacular Press Act</b> was passed in <b>1878</b>.","expimage": ""},
"53": {"questext": "The Second Afghan War (1878-80), fought under Lord Lytton's 'Forward Policy', coincided with the passage of which act restricting weapons?","options": ["Vernacular Press Act","Arms Act (1878)","Official Secrets Act","Indian Councils Act"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Arms Act (1878)</b><br><br>Lord Lytton's <b>Forward Policy</b> led to the <b>Second Afghan War (1878-80)</b>, alongside the passage of the <b>Arms Act in 1878</b>. Lytton was also a noted poet, novelist, and essayist known in the literary world as <b>'Owen Meredith'</b>.","expimage": ""},
"54": {"questext": "The First Delhi Durbar was organized on 1 January 1877 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Ripon","Lord Lytton","Lord Dufferin","Lord Curzon"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Lytton</b><br><br>Lord Lytton organized the <b>First Delhi Durbar on 1 January 1877</b>. He also reduced the <b>maximum age limit for entry into Civil Services examinations from 21 years to 19 years</b>.","expimage": ""},
"55": {"questext": "Local self-government was introduced in India in 1882 by which Viceroy, earning him the title 'Father of Local Self-Government'?","options": ["Lord Lytton","Lord Ripon","Lord Dufferin","Lord Lansdowne"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Ripon</b><br><br>Lord Ripon (1880-1884) introduced <b>Local Self-Government in 1882</b>, earning him the title <b>'Father of Local Self-Government in India'</b>. His tenure also saw the passage of the <b>First (regular) Factory Act and Census</b>, along with the <b>Hunter Commission on education</b>.","expimage": ""},
"56": {"questext": "The Ilbert Bill controversy, which sparked strong opposition from Europeans in India, occurred during whose tenure?","options": ["Lord Lytton","Lord Ripon","Lord Dufferin","Lord Lansdowne"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Ripon</b><br><br>The <b>Ilbert Bill controversy</b> occurred during Lord Ripon's tenure. In the <b>1909 Congress session</b>, <b>Pt. Madan Mohan Malaviya</b> stated that <b>Ripon was the most popular among Indian Viceroys</b>. Ripon also repealed the <b>Vernacular Press Act in 1882</b>, earning him the title <b>'Liberator of the Press'</b>.","expimage": ""},
"57": {"questext": "Which social reformer described Lord Ripon as the 'saviour of India'?","options": ["Annie Besant","Florence Nightingale","Sister Nivedita","Margaret Cousins"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Florence Nightingale</b><br><br><b>Florence Nightingale</b> described Lord Ripon as the <b>'saviour of India'</b>. Ripon is also credited with introducing a <b>Policy of Financial Decentralisation</b> during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"58": {"questext": "The Indian National Congress was founded on 28 December 1885 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Ripon","Lord Dufferin","Lord Lansdowne","Lord Elgin-II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Dufferin</b><br><br>The <b>Indian National Congress was founded on 28 December 1885</b> during Lord Dufferin's tenure (1884-1888). His period also witnessed the <b>Third Burmese War (1885-86)</b>, leading to the annexation of Burma, along with the <b>Bengal Tenancy Act (1885)</b> and <b>Punjab Tenancy Act (1887)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"59": {"questext": "The Indian Councils Act of 1892 was passed during the tenure of which Viceroy, who also divided Civil Services into three tiers?","options": ["Lord Dufferin","Lord Lansdowne","Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Lansdowne</b><br><br>Lord Lansdowne (1888-1894) passed the <b>Indian Councils Act of 1892</b>. During his tenure, the <b>Second Factory Act (1891)</b> was passed, and the Civil Services were divided into <b>Imperial, Provincial, and Subordinate Services</b>.","expimage": ""},
"60": {"questext": "The Durand Commission, appointed to demarcate the border between British India and Afghanistan, was set up during whose Viceroyalty?","options": ["Lord Dufferin","Lord Lansdowne","Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Lansdowne</b><br><br>The <b>Durand Commission</b> was appointed during Lord Lansdowne's tenure to demarcate the border between <b>British India (present-day Pakistan) and Afghanistan</b>, resulting in the <b>Durand Line</b>.","expimage": ""},
"61": {"questext": "The Great Famine of 1896-97 and the Lyall Commission on famine occurred during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Lansdowne","Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon","Lord Minto-II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Elgin-II</b><br><br>The <b>Great Famine of 1896-97</b> occurred during Lord Elgin-II's tenure (1894-1899), leading to the appointment of the <b>Lyall Commission on famine</b>. His period is also associated with the statement, <i>\"We have conquered India by the power of the sword, and by the power of the sword we shall subjugate it.\"</i>","expimage": ""},
"62": {"questext": "The Chapekar brothers, who murdered two British officers during the plague outbreak in Poona, were active during whose Viceroyalty?","options": ["Lord Ripon","Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon","Lord Minto-II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Elgin-II</b><br><br>During Lord Elgin-II's tenure, a <b>plague outbreak in Poona</b> led to the <b>murder of two British officers by the Chapekar brothers</b>. The <b>'Welby Commission'</b> was also formed in <b>1895</b> to investigate Indian expenditure.","expimage": ""},
"63": {"questext": "The Ancient Monuments Preservation Act was passed in 1904 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon","Lord Minto-II","Lord Hardinge-II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Curzon</b><br><br>Lord Curzon (1899-1905) passed the <b>Ancient Monuments Preservation Act in 1904</b> and established the <b>Agriculture Research Institute at Pusa in Bihar</b>. He was regarded as the <b>most unpopular Viceroy of India</b>, and <b>Ronaldshay</b> wrote his biography.","expimage": ""},
"64": {"questext": "Gopal Krishna Gokhale famously compared Lord Curzon to which Mughal emperor, calling him the 'Aurangzeb of modern India'?","options": ["Akbar","Aurangzeb","Shah Jahan","Jahangir"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Aurangzeb</b><br><br>Citing his authoritarian policies, <b>Gokhale</b> called Lord Curzon the <b>'Aurangzeb of modern India'</b>. During Curzon's tenure, a <b>central intelligence system was established</b>, and in <b>1901</b>, India's <b>first caste-based census</b> was conducted.","expimage": ""},
"65": {"questext": "The Police Commission of 1902, formed to improve police administration under Lord Curzon, was chaired by whom?","options": ["Sir Thomas Raleigh","Andrew Fraser","Lord Welby","Lord Lyall"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Andrew Fraser</b><br><br>The <b>Police Commission (1902)</b> was formed under the chairmanship of <b>Andrew Fraser</b> to improve police administration. The <b>University Commission (1902)</b>, chaired by <b>Sir Thomas Raleigh</b>, led to the <b>University Reform Act of 1904</b>. Curzon's tenure also saw the passage of the <b>Official Secrets Act (1904)</b>, further increasing government control.","expimage": ""},
"66": {"questext": "The Younghusband Mission to Tibet (1903-04) was undertaken during the tenure of which Viceroy, who also established the Archaeological Survey of India?","options": ["Lord Elgin-II","Lord Curzon","Lord Minto-II","Lord Hardinge-II"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Curzon</b><br><br>Lord Curzon undertook the <b>'Younghusband Mission' to Tibet (1903-04)</b>. He also established the <b>Department of Industries and Commerce</b> and the <b>Archaeological Survey of India</b> during his tenure.","expimage": ""},
"67": {"questext": "Lord Curzon resigned in August 1905 following a dispute with which Commander-in-Chief?","options": ["Lord Roberts","Lord Kitchener","Lord Wavell","Lord Lake"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Kitchener</b><br><br>Lord Curzon resigned in <b>August 1905</b> due to a dispute with Commander-in-Chief <b>Lord Kitchener</b>, shortly after the <b>Partition of Bengal (1905)</b>. He was known as an advocate of <b>extreme centralisation and autocratic rule</b>.","expimage": ""},
"68": {"questext": "Lord Curzon, criticising the Indian education system, famously said the East is a university where a student never gets what?","options": ["An education","A degree","A job","A scholarship"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>A degree</b><br><br>Criticising India's education system, Lord Curzon remarked, <i>\"The East is a university where a student never gets a degree.\"</i> Satirising the Calcutta Municipality, he said he would <i>\"like to be the Mayor of Calcutta after the Viceroy.\"</i> On the Congress, he remarked, <i>\"Congress is now mortal and I wish to contribute to its peaceful death.\"</i>","expimage": ""},
"69": {"questext": "The Morley-Minto Reforms of 1909 were introduced during the tenure of which Viceroy, following the Surat session split in Congress?","options": ["Lord Curzon","Lord Minto-II","Lord Hardinge-II","Lord Chelmsford"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Minto-II</b><br><br>Lord Minto-II (1905-1910) oversaw the <b>Anti-Partition and Swadeshi movements</b>, the <b>Surat session and split in the Congress</b>, and the introduction of the <b>Morley-Minto Reforms (1909)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"70": {"questext": "The Muslim League was founded in 1906 during Lord Minto-II's tenure. Who was appointed as the first Indian member of the Viceroy's Executive Council in the same period?",
"options": ["S.P. Sinha","Motilal Nehru","G.K. Gokhale","M.M. Malaviya"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>S.P. Sinha</b><br><br>The <b>Muslim League</b> was founded in <b>1906</b> by the <b>Aga Khan, Nawab of Dacca</b>, and others. <b>S.P. Sinha</b> was appointed as the <b>first Indian member of the Viceroy's Executive Council</b>. During this period, <b>Khudiram Bose was hanged</b> and <b>Bal Gangadhar Tilak was sentenced to six years' imprisonment</b> for treason (1908).","expimage": ""},
"71": {"questext": "The imperial capital of India was transferred to Delhi during the tenure of which Viceroy, who also annulled the Partition of Bengal?","options": ["Lord Minto-II","Lord Hardinge-II","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Reading"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Hardinge-II</b><br><br>Lord Hardinge-II (1910-1916) oversaw the <b>annulment of the Partition of Bengal</b> and the <b>transfer of the imperial capital to Delhi</b>. His tenure also saw the <b>death of G.K. Gokhale in 1915</b>.","expimage": ""},
"72": {"questext": "The Hindu Mahasabha was founded in 1915 during Lord Hardinge-II's tenure by whom?","options": ["K.B. Hedgewar","M.M. Malaviya","S.N. Banerjee","B.G. Tilak"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>M.M. Malaviya</b><br><br>The <b>Hindu Mahasabha</b> was founded in <b>1915</b> by <b>Madan Mohan Malaviya</b>. Lord Hardinge-II's tenure also saw the <b>Third Delhi Durbar (1911)</b> and the appointment of the <b>Eslington Commission (1912)</b>, which proposed appointing <b>25 percent Indians</b> in the civil services.","expimage": ""},
"73": {"questext": "Banaras Hindu University, established in 1916 during Lord Hardinge-II's tenure, was founded by whom?","options": ["K.B. Hedgewar","Madan Mohan Malaviya","S.N. Banerjee","David Hare"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Madan Mohan Malaviya</b><br><br><b>Banaras Hindu University</b> was established in <b>1916</b> by <b>Madan Mohan Malaviya</b>. The <b>First World War began in 1914</b>, and the <b>Home Rule Leagues</b> were formed in <b>1916</b> during Hardinge-II's tenure.","expimage": ""},
"74": {"questext": "The Lucknow Pact of 1916, achieved through the efforts of B.G. Tilak, coincided with the reunion of Congress at which session?","options": ["Surat Session","Lucknow Session","Lahore Session","Haripur Session"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lucknow Session</b><br><br>The <b>Lucknow Session (1916)</b> saw the <b>reunion of the Congress</b> and the signing of the <b>Lucknow Pact</b> through the efforts of <b>B.G. Tilak</b>, bringing the Congress and Muslim League together. Around this time, the <b>Indian Liberal Federation</b> was formed by <b>S.N. Banerjee</b>.","expimage": ""},
"75": {"questext": "The Jallianwala Bagh Massacre took place on 13 April 1919 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Hardinge-II","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Reading","Lord Irwin"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Chelmsford</b><br><br>The <b>Jallianwala Bagh Massacre</b> occurred on <b>13 April 1919</b> during Lord Chelmsford's tenure (1916-1921). This period also saw the <b>Khilafat Movement (1919-20)</b> and the launch of the <b>Non-Cooperation Movement</b>.","expimage": ""},
"76": {"questext": "The Champaran Movement (1917) and Kheda Satyagraha (1918), led by Gandhi, occurred during whose Viceroyalty?","options": ["Lord Hardinge-II","Lord Chelmsford","Lord Reading","Lord Irwin"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Chelmsford</b><br><br>During Lord Chelmsford's tenure, Gandhi established the <b>Sabarmati Ashram (1917)</b> and led the <b>Champaran Movement (1917)</b>, the <b>Ahmedabad Mill Satyagraha (1918)</b>, and the <b>Kheda Satyagraha (1918)</b>. <b>Sir S.P. Sinha</b> was appointed the <b>first Indian Lieutenant Governor of Bihar</b> during this period.","expimage": ""},
"77": {"questext": "The Rowlatt Act and the Government of India Act were both passed in 1919 following the Montagu-Chelmsford Declarations of which year?","options": ["1916","1917","1918","1920"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1917</b><br><br>The <b>Montagu-Chelmsford Declarations (1917)</b> paved the way for the <b>Government of India Act (1919)</b> and the <b>Rowlatt Act (1919)</b>. This period also witnessed the beginning of <b>dual rule (Diarchy)</b> in the provinces.","expimage": ""},
"78": {"questext": "The Anglo-Mohammedan Oriental College was renamed Aligarh Muslim University in which year, during Lord Chelmsford's tenure?","options": ["1916","1919","1920","1922"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>1920</b><br><br>The <b>Anglo-Mohammedan Oriental College</b> was renamed <b>Aligarh Muslim University in 1920</b>. Bal Gangadhar Tilak also passed away on <b>1 August 1920</b> during Lord Chelmsford's tenure.","expimage": ""},
"79": {"questext": "The Chauri Chaura incident, which led Gandhi to withdraw the Non-Cooperation Movement, occurred on which date?","options": ["1 August 1920","5 February 1922","13 April 1919","23 March 1931"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>5 February 1922</b><br><br>The <b>Chauri Chaura incident</b> occurred on <b>5 February 1922</b> during Lord Chelmsford's tenure. This period also saw the formation of the <b>Swaraj Party by C.R. Das and Motilal Nehru (1923)</b> and the founding of the <b>Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh (RSS) by K.B. Hedgewar (1925)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"80": {"questext": "Lord Reading (1921-1926), the only Jewish Viceroy of India, repealed which controversial legislation?","options": ["Vernacular Press Act","Rowlatt Act","Arms Act","Official Secrets Act"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Rowlatt Act</b><br><br>Lord Reading (1921-1926), the <b>only Jewish Viceroy</b> of India, oversaw the <b>repeal of the Rowlatt Act</b>. His tenure also saw <b>simultaneous Civil Service examinations</b> held in India and England (1923).","expimage": ""},
"81": {"questext": "The Kakori Train Robbery of 1925 occurred during Lord Reading's tenure. Which committee's recommendation led to the separation of the Railway Budget from the General Budget?","options": ["Acworth Committee","Sandhurst Committee","Hartog Committee","Welby Commission"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Acworth Committee</b><br><br>The <b>Kakori Train Robbery</b> took place in <b>1925</b> during Lord Reading's tenure. The <b>Acworth Committee</b> recommended separating the <b>Railway Budget from the General Budget</b>, with the first separate railway budget presented in <b>1924-25</b>. A committee under <b>Sandhurst</b> was also formed for military reforms, with <b>Motilal Nehru</b> as its Indian member.","expimage": ""},
"82": {"questext": "The Lahore Session of Congress (1929), which declared 'Poorna Swaraj', was held during the tenure of which Viceroy, who had earlier faced the Simon Commission boycott?","options": ["Lord Reading","Lord Irwin","Lord Willingdon","Lord Linlithgow"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Irwin</b><br><br>Lord Irwin (1926-1931) faced the <b>Simon Commission and its boycott</b>. The <b>Nehru Report</b> was drafted during this period, followed by the <b>Lahore Session of Congress (1929)</b>, which declared <b>'Poorna Swaraj'</b> as the goal.","expimage": ""},
"83": {"questext": "The Civil Disobedience Movement and Dandi March of 1930 were followed by which pact signed at the First Round Table Conference under Lord Irwin?","options": ["Poona Pact","Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931)","Lucknow Pact","Nagpur Pact"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931)</b><br><br>The <b>Civil Disobedience Movement</b> and <b>Dandi March</b> were launched in <b>1930</b>. The <b>First Round Table Conference</b> was followed by the signing of the <b>Gandhi-Irwin Pact (1931)</b>. Earlier, the <b>Hartog Butler Committee</b> on Princely States was appointed in <b>1927</b>.","expimage": ""},
"84": {"questext": "The Sharda Act of 1930, passed during Lord Irwin's tenure, fixed the marriage age for girls at how many years?","options": ["12","14","16","18"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>14</b><br><br>The <b>Sharda Act (1930)</b> fixed the marriage age at <b>18 years for boys</b> and <b>14 years for girls</b>. During Lord Irwin's tenure, <b>Sanders</b>, Assistant Superintendent of Police at Lahore, was murdered, leading to the <b>Lahore Conspiracy Case</b> and the death of <b>Jatin Das</b> due to a prolonged fast (1929). A <b>Royal Commission on Agriculture</b> also led to the establishment of the <b>Imperial Council of Agricultural Research (1929)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"85": {"questext": "The Communal Award of 1932, which led to the Poona Pact between Gandhi and Ambedkar, was announced by whom?","options": ["Ramsay MacDonald","Lord Willingdon","Lord Irwin","Stanley Baldwin"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Ramsay MacDonald</b><br><br>The <b>Communal Award (1932)</b> was announced by British Prime Minister <b>Ramsay MacDonald</b> during Lord Willingdon's tenure (1931-1936), leading to the <b>Poona Pact between Gandhi and Ambedkar (1932)</b>. This period also saw the <b>Second and Third Round Table Conferences (1931 and 1932)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"86": {"questext": "The Indian Military Academy (IMA) at Dehradun was established in 1932 during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Irwin","Lord Willingdon","Lord Linlithgow","Lord Wavell"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Willingdon</b><br><br>The <b>Indian Military Academy (IMA)</b> at Dehradun was established in <b>1932</b> during Lord Willingdon's tenure. The <b>Government of India Act, 1935</b> was passed, and the <b>Socialist Party</b> was founded by <b>Acharya Narendra Dev</b> and <b>Jai Prakash Narayan (1934)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"87": {"questext": "The Government of India Act, 1935 provided for the separation of which territory from India?","options": ["Ceylon","Burma","Sindh","Bengal"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Burma</b><br><br>The <b>Act of 1935</b> provided for the <b>separation of Burma from India</b>. During Lord Linlithgow's tenure (1936-1944), the Muslim League observed <b>'Deliverance Day' in 1939</b>, and <b>Provincial elections</b> were held in <b>1936-37</b>.","expimage": ""},
"88": {"questext": "Subhash Chandra Bose became President of the Congress at which 1938 session, during Lord Linlithgow's tenure?","options": ["Lucknow Session","Haripur Session","Lahore Session","Tripuri Session"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Haripur Session</b><br><br>Subhash Chandra Bose became President of the Congress at the <b>Haripur Session in 1938</b>. During Lord Linlithgow's tenure, <b>World War II began (1939)</b>, and the <b>Congress provincial governments resigned (1939)</b>.","expimage": ""},
"89": {"questext": "The Forward Bloc was established in 1939 following the Tripuri crisis and resignation of which Congress leader?","options": ["Jawaharlal Nehru","Subhash Chandra Bose","C. Rajagopalachari","Motilal Nehru"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Subhash Chandra Bose</b><br><br>The <b>Tripuri crisis</b> in the Congress led to <b>Subhash Chandra Bose's resignation</b> and the establishment of the <b>Forward Bloc (1939)</b>. Bose later <b>escaped from India in 1941</b> and established the <b>Azad Hind Fauj in 1943</b>.","expimage": ""},
"90": {"questext": "The 'August Proposal' was announced by the Viceroy Lord Linlithgow on which date in 1940?","options": ["8 August 1940","15 August 1940","26 January 1940","23 March 1940"],"correct": "1","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>8 August 1940</b><br><br>The <b>'August Proposal'</b> was announced by Lord Linlithgow on <b>8 August 1940</b>. Gandhi's <b>personal Satyagraha</b> began from the <b>Pawnar Ashram (1940)</b>, and the <b>Cripps Mission</b> arrived in India in <b>1942</b>, followed by the launch of the <b>Quit India Movement</b>.","expimage": ""},
"91": {"questext": "The Muslim League's Karachi session in 1943 gave which slogan?","options": ["Do or Die","Divide and Quit","Simon Go Back","Direct Action"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Divide and Quit</b><br><br>The <b>Karachi session of the Muslim League (1943)</b> gave the slogan <b>'Divide and Quit'</b>. This period also saw the <b>C.R. Formula</b> proposed by <b>C. Rajagopalachari</b>, the failure of the <b>Gandhi-Jinnah dialogue</b>, the <b>Wavell Plan</b> and <b>Shimla Conference</b>, and the <b>INA Trials</b>.","expimage": ""},
"92": {"questext": "The Cabinet Mission, comprising Lawrence, Cripps, and Alexander, was sent to India during the tenure of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Linlithgow","Lord Wavell","Lord Mountbatten","Lord Irwin"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Wavell</b><br><br>The <b>Cabinet Mission</b>, comprising <b>Lawrence, Cripps, and Alexander</b>, was sent to India during Lord Wavell's tenure (1944-1947). His period also witnessed the <b>Naval Mutiny of 1946</b>.","expimage": ""},
"93": {"questext": "The Interim Government, formed by Congress in September 1946, had Lord Wavell as President and who as Vice President?","options": ["Sardar Patel","Jawaharlal Nehru","C. Rajagopalachari","Rajendra Prasad"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Jawaharlal Nehru</b><br><br>The <b>Interim Government</b>, established by Congress in <b>September 1946</b>, had <b>Wavell as President</b> and <b>Nehru as Vice President</b>. This followed the <b>Direct Action Day called by the Muslim League on 16 August 1946</b>. World War II had ended in <b>1945</b>.","expimage": ""},
"94": {"questext": "British Prime Minister Clement Attlee announced the independence of India on 20 February 1947, just before the arrival of which Viceroy?","options": ["Lord Wavell","Lord Mountbatten","Lord Linlithgow","C. Rajagopalachari"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Lord Mountbatten</b><br><br>British Prime Minister <b>Clement Attlee announced the independence of India on 20 February 1947</b>, just before Lord Mountbatten took charge. The <b>Partition of India</b> was carried out as per the <b>3rd June Plan</b>, and the <b>Indian Independence Act</b> was passed on <b>18 July 1947</b>.","expimage": ""},
"95": {"questext": "Lord Mountbatten, the first Governor-General of independent India and last British Viceroy, was in office during which tragic event?","options": ["Jallianwala Bagh Massacre","Assassination of Mahatma Gandhi","Chauri Chaura Incident","Kakori Train Robbery"],"correct": "2","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Assassination of Mahatma Gandhi</b><br><br>Lord Mountbatten (February 1947 – June 1948) was the <b>first Governor-General of independent India and last British Viceroy</b>. His tenure saw the <b>emergence of India and Pakistan as two separate independent countries</b> and the tragic <b>assassination of Mahatma Gandhi</b>.","expimage": ""},
"96": {"questext": "After the Constitution was implemented on 26 January 1950, the post of Governor-General was abolished. Who was chosen as India's first President?","options": ["C. Rajagopalachari","Jawaharlal Nehru","Rajendra Prasad","Sardar Patel"],"correct": "3","quesimage": "","exptext": "<b>Rajendra Prasad</b><br><br><b>C. Rajagopalachari</b> served as the <b>last Governor-General of India</b> and the <b>first Indian Governor-General of independent India (21 June 1948 – 26 January 1950)</b>. After the <b>Constitution was implemented on 26 January 1950</b>, the post of Governor-General was abolished, and <b>Rajendra Prasad</b> was chosen as India's <b>first President</b>.","expimage": ""}};
